Title: 
 Comprehension's Role in Persuasion: The Case of Its Moderating Effect on the Persuasive Impact of 
Journal: Journal of Consumer Research
Pages: 52-62
Issue: 1
Volume: 18
Year: 1991
Month:  June 
Abstract:

 A study of reactions to a novel product attributed the invention to
 either an expert or a novice. Comprehension of the product description was
 manipulated by varying information exposure time (Study 1) and contextual
 prior knowledge (Study 2). As predicted by the heuristic-systematic model
 comprehensibility moderated the persuasive impact of source expertise.
 When comprehension was low, subjects relied on the inventor's expertise in
 forming their attitudes toward the product, but when comprehension and
 hence, systematic processing were higher, source expertise had no impact
 on subjects' attitudes. In a pilot study, however, subjects attributed
 comprehensibility to the source and derogated incomprehensible
 communications.


